Offering a captive-bred, three-year-old pair of Kaiser Newts (Neurergus kaiseri), one of the rarest and most beautiful newt species in the world. We‚Äôve been keeping and breeding Kaiser Newts from our original group since 2011, with excellent long-term success and healthy bloodlines. They thrive in hard, well-filtered water with a pH around 8.0, and we use limestone in the aquarium to help maintain water hardness and stability. Best kept between 60‚Äì70¬∞F, with breeding often triggered in the low 60s. These newts are extremely rare, and preserving their captive population is a top priority, so they‚Äôre best suited for responsible, experienced amphibian keepers. Please note that Kaiser Newts are expert escape artists and must be housed in a secure aquarium with no gaps or openings. title: Neon Day Gecko Juveniles
description:
Phelsuma klemmeri unsexed juveniles. Happy and healthy, these guys are growing fast! If you are looking to set up your own breeding group, we recommend you start here. Group discounts available upon request starting at groups of 4+ individuals.

Juveniles ship starting at 1.5 - 3 months of age on average depending on size, at which point they are well started. If you purchase multiple klemmeri, we will provide unrelated genetics where possible and do our best to ensure a diverse pool of genetics for your group. Our breeding Phelsuma klemmeri adults were originally sourced from as many different breeders as we could find, with multiple unrelated lines from each source whenever possible. We also occasionally bring in new genetics. As a result, we now have many unrelated genetic lines available.

 

Phelsuma klemmeri, commonly known as the Neon Day Gecko, is an endangered species of small day gecko which exhibit some of the brightest colors amongst all geckos. Endemic to northwest Madagascar, klemmeri are most commonly found in bamboo forests. Maxing out at a size of roughly 3.5 inches, both mature and juvenile klemmeri display vibrant yellow-green heads and turquoise bodies accompanied by bold black stripes on their flanks. Sexual dimorphism is not seen in color or pattern for this species, so females are equally stunning as males!

Unlike most Phelsuma, klemmeri are social and do well in groups. Parents do not eat their young as is common with most day geckos. Hatchlings can be raised with the parents, although they should be removed before reaching sexual maturity to avoid territorial disputes among males and to prevent inbreeding. We keep our klemmeri in 1.3 groups and raise some of the young in with the parents. Social interactions can regularly be observed amongst the group, ranging from head bobbing, tail waving, to walking up to another gecko for a greeting lick on the nose! These endearing social interactions combined with the natural curiosity and observant nature of klemmeri makes them endlessly captivating in the terrarium.

We have found Phelsuma klemmeri to be resilient and easy to breed under proper conditions. Female klemmeri in breeding groups produce a pair of eggs roughly every 3-5 weeks. They produce continuously throughout the majority of the year, with each pair slowing down only for several months out of the year.

title: 2025 Burmese Star Tortoise - Holdback Release
description:
This listing is for the buyer‚Äôs pick of one of my pictured (I am happy to send additional photos for serious inquiries) holdback 2025 Burmese stars. All were born in April, were incubated for female, and are absolutely thriving. They are also the offspring of the best tortoise I‚Äôve ever worked with - she‚Äôs absolutely incredible. If you have the space for a medium to large(ish) sized tortoise, I don't think there's a better candidate for a pet than a Burmese star. With proper socialization, Burmese stars are "shell dogs". My adults rapidly approach me whenever they see me, love head and shell scratches/rubs, and will follow me around the yard when I let them. 

Burmese star tortoises are why I'm here; they were the first species I ever had, and I fell in love with them to the point where I've built my reptile endeavors around them. 

Anyone who does not live in a relatively warm climate should know that Burmese star tortoise females can reach 12+ inches and weigh 15+ pounds. Successfully keeping these inside can be accomplished, but know it will take a substantial indoor enclosure with ample lighting (heat and UVB). As larger animals, they can also be quite smelly, so keep that in mind. 

Burmese stars do wonderfully when kept outdoors. They thrive with high humidity (unlike Indian and Sri Lankan stars) and are rock solid animals. 

You will be able to text or DM me at any time on my cell or IG for a lifetime of care guidance. I will never hold someone's lack of experience against them when inquiring about an animal. The right animal for you is the one you want the most. I'm also happy to answer any and all questions even if you you're interested but are not sure Burmese stars are for you. 

With proper care, these animals should live at least in excess of 50 years. These are forever pets. But, I do understand life circumstances can change. I care very much about the animals not only going to, but also remaining at, good homes. If, for any reason, you can no longer care for an animal, please let me know, and I will try to help you find a new home for your shell buddy.
